review_blob: Bottle. Poured a really dark amber with off-white fizzy head. Would like to try again when Im not eating spicy asian food, but overall this isnt a bad beer. It seems to lack a little bit in every category, but not bad.

Bottle. Poured a orange/bronze color a little light than most IPAs. Despite reading a lot of reviews that said the head was fizzy and dissipated, my pour created a 2-finger foamy head that lasted throughout. I loved this beer. Lots of hops and citrus...and a super long finish. Cheers!
Bottle. Poured a beautiful orange/copper color with fizzy white head. Lots of aroma or apricots and citrus. Very refreshing. If you can find it, buy it!

Bottle. Poured into 12 oz tulip. Creamy white head. Muddy color--sort of like sweet tea with lemonade. Very light beer, with almost no finish. Great flavor, just not a whole lot of it. Has light floral notes, but mostly citrus, hops and malts almost non-existent....pretty watery. Very approachable White Ale, but theres a reason why this is seasonal....this simply could not make it year round.
This beer has all the qualities of a brown ale. Good balance of hops and malts. SLightly bitter aftertaste. Good affordable Brown Ale. Will definitely get again.

Bottle. Poured a pitch black with frothy off-white tan head. Very light density, and slightly watery in the mouth. Very approachable dark beer, and very affordable. Overall, I think it lacks any uniqueness. Good beer, but not my style.

Bottle. Poured into Tulip 12oz glass. Elegant amber color with thin, off-white head. One of my all-time favorites. NUtty and smooth as it goes down with a slightly bitter aftertaste that is quite pleasing to the palate. This is always a safe beer to go back to.Enjoy!

Bottle. Pine needles. Holy cow does this ever taste like pine needles. This is a strongly spiced Tripel, with loads of pine, hops, citris, and clove. This seemed to be a stronger, more mouth-puckering, Tripel. I prefer a smoother beer, such as Chimay Cinq Cents, but this beer is seemingly gaining popularity. Not on my top list, but a drinkable Abbey Tripel.

Bottle. I agree with Lumpy in that it has an "iced tea" body. It has a delightful, easy to drink, flavor that is smooth, and a bit citris. It is very sweet, and is a very approachable Amber Ale. Great beer!
beer_name: Widmer Brothers Drop Top Amber Ale

review_blob:
Bottle. Poured into a pint. 
Very flowery aroma. Poured very dark brown with frothy tan head. Good balance of malts and is a very smooth Old Ale.

I, along with many others, saw the handsome quart bottle and gave this beer a chance. It is extremely watery and really lacks on the flavor. There is, however, a hint of espresso and roasted malts, but it truly does not live up to its name. Watery and Mild.
Beautiful amber color with a thick, fizzy off-white head that quickly dissipates. Strong hops and well balanced malts with a pleasantly bitter/sour aftertaste.
Poured from Pub-Pour can. Not as sweet as some other Stout Pub-Pour beers. The dark roasted malts have a pleasantly bitter aftertaste, and leaves the palate with hints of espresso.

I agree with JLAudio in that it is a smooth beer....smooth as water. This is the beer I keep at my house for when a friend, who is not a beer drinker, feels left out. Has an OK hoppy flavor, but where is the barley? I think they forgot to add some ingredients here....

As with other Modelo beers, I do not advise to drink these without food. Particularly for the Negra, I prefer to drink this with some heavy mexican dishes such as enchiladas, or tamales. Has an OK nutty aftertaste and slight hints of malt.

This is a beer that I would never get on its own. However, it is a great thirst quencher, and goes pretty good with some hot wings. It cleanes the palate fairly well and creates a good balance with the hot wings.
Bottle. Poured a dark amber with little aroma. Had a pleasant maltiness, but overall was pretty watery. Had a good flavor, though  it was weak.
Pours a golden straw color with frothy white head. Very strong citrus notes, but a little sour aftertaste that was not so pleasant.

Very pleasable Stout. Pours a very dark brown with slightly aromatic head. The texture is a bit thinner than I had expected, but, all around had a good taste. However, I was a bit surprised to see how many 3.5 and higher ratings this beer has received. I guess it just did not appeal to me as much. This is a good beer, but I highly recommend the Youngs Double Chocolate Stout, or, just going with a Guinness Extra Stout.
A good smooth beer with strong hints of malt, with a slightly nutty aftertaste. Will definitely buy again.
